<HEADLINE>
<P>
INTEL CONFIRMS PLANS TO BUILD $2.2-BILLION CHIP PLANT IN OREGON 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Intel Corp. made it official Thursday: It will build what may become the most 
expensive computer chip factory in the world in this Portland suburb. 
</P>
<P>
 Word of the $2.2-billion project began leaking this summer as the company 
prepared to ask Washington County for a tax break to build the semiconductor 
manufacturing and development center. 
</P>
<P>
 But official approval of the project was delayed by executives at Intel 
headquarters in Santa Clara, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
 The 300-acre company campus and plant may be the most expensive single 
expansion project ever undertaken by a U.S. company, analysts say. 
</P>
<P>
 Motorola and Advanced Micro Devices are expected to build plants in Austin, 
Tex., costing more than $1 billion. 
</P>
<P>
 Intel engineers will use the Hillsboro facility to develop new generations of 
faster, more powerful chips to succeed the industry-standard Pentium, being 
challenged by competitors such as the PowerPC microprocessor. 
</P>
