<HEADLINE>
<P>
RSVP / INTO THE NIGHT: REACHING NEW LEVELS OF DUMB 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BILL HIGGINS, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Scene: Tuesday's benefit world premiere of New Line Cinema's "Dumb and 
Dumber" at the Cinerama Dome. A party followed at the Hollywood Palladium. This 
is a film that wallows ecstatically in the joy of dopiness. "It's on the 
cutting edge of stupidity," said studio chairman Bob Shaye. 
</P>
<P>
 How Dumb? "We wanted this to be the dumbest premiere of all time," producer 
Brad Krevoy said. "We were going to have the red carpet lead to doors that 
didn't open. Then we decided that wasn't dumb enough." 
</P>
<P>
 Who Was There: The film's stars, Jim Carrey and Jeff Daniels; director Peter 
Farrelly; producers Krevoy, Charles Wessler and Steve Stabler; among the 1,000 
guests were Richard Pryor (who drove himself on an electric three-wheeled 
vehicle), Dennis Miller, Pauly Shore, Magic Johnson, Jennifer Tilly, Stephen 
Baldwin, Rodney Dangerfield, Mike Marcus, Sid Ganis, David Colden, Joely Fisher 
and Dwight Yoakam. 
</P>
<P>
 Quoted: "This movie is about two of the dumbest guys you've ever met in your 
life," Daniels said. "The combined IQ of these two characters would be that of 
Forrest Gump." 
</P>
<P>
 Besides Dumb: Fortunately, the film wasn't merely dumb. It was also tasteless. 
Among the sources of jokes were urine swigging, parakeet decapitation, 
laxatives, blind children, bestiality, flatulence, saliva, belching, death by 
poisoning, and Leslie Abramson. "I hate PC movies," said New Line President 
Mike De Luca. "Humor is for taboo subjects." 
</P>
<P>
 Overheard: "It lives up to its title"; "It was more than dumb. It rose to 
stupidity." And, "Who was the guy who said 'No one ever went broke 
underestimating the taste of the American public?' " 
</P>
<P>
 Money Matters: Tickets were $150 each and more than $100,000 was raised for 
the Magic Johnson Foundation. The funds will be used for AIDS patient care 
facilities. 
</P>
<P>
 Buzz: It's universally expected to be a hit. The timing of the film's release 
is too perfect, coming at a time when the country is dumbing down, was the 
consensus. One guest said that if the country's dumb enough to elect Newt 
Gingrich Speaker of the House, it's dumb enough for this. 
</P>
<P>
 Hollywood Wisdom: "For the audience it's intended for, this movie will do 
spectacularly," an exec from a rival studio said. "For the audience it's not 
intended for, who cares?" 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA120994-0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 106416 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
December 9, 1994, Friday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Life & Style; Part E; Page 12; Column 1; View Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
433 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
RSVP; PROOF THAT DREAMS DO COME TRUE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEANNINE STEIN, TIMES SOCIETY WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 "This is like realizing your dream," said Lilly Tartikoff as she surveyed a 
room filled with celebrities, entertainment industry power brokers and super 
models. 
</P>
<P>
 But it wasn't just the company she was describing. Tartikoff's dream has been 
to fund breast cancer research and increase awareness and education about 
women's health issues. 
</P>
<P>
 In five years she's done that, and then some. 
</P>
<P>
 Wednesday night marked the fifth annual Fire and Ice Ball, a black-tie gala to 
raise money for the Revlon/UCLA Women's Cancer Research Program. The event was 
held in two 20th Century Fox sound stages to accommodate a half-hour show of 
Giorgio Armani's spring and summer men's and women's fashions. 
</P>
<P>
 The $1,000-per-person ball is expected to raise $1.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
 But Revlon Chairman Ronald Perelman, generous guy that he is, kicked in 
another $7.5 million, which will create the Revlon/UCLA Women's Health Research 
Program, as well as continue to support the cancer research. 
</P>
<P>
 "Mr. Armani wanted to do something especially for women," Tartikoff said of 
the designer's involvement. 
</P>
<P>
 "I was thrilled. He's such a perfectionist -- I keep equating him to George 
Balanchine (for whom she danced at the New York City Ballet). It's working with 
another artistic genius. I keep having deja vu. " 
</P>
<P>
 Armani found this "a very big compliment." 
</P>
<P>
 Cold temperatures didn't deter the 1,200 really beautiful people from showing 
up. 
</P>
<P>
 In the audience (instead of on the runway) were models Cindy Crawford, Claudia 
Schiffer, Veronica Webb and Linda Evangelista, as well as Jim Carrey, Robbie 
Robertson, Penny Marshall, Herb Ross and Lee Radziwill, Mariel Hemingway, 
Michelle Pfeiffer, Jay Leno, Ellen DeGeneres, Brendan Fraser, Mickey Rourke and 
Antonio Banderas. 
</P>
<P>
 Said Carrey, "I usually don't do this kind of thing. I came for the cause and 
the company." 
</P>
<P>
 Following the show, guests entered another sound stage, this one designed by 
Armani to look like an Italian garden, complete with hedges, fruit-dripping 
candelabra and people dressed in 18th-Century period costumes. 
</P>
<P>
 During speeches, Tartikoff thanked her co-chairs Rupert Murdoch and Perelman. 
</P>
<P>
 Isabella Rossellini told emotional stories of her mother Ingrid Bergman's 
struggle with breast cancer. 
</P>
<P>
 Dinner was a table-hopping festival although some guests actually stayed put 
during the four-course meal and just craned their necks to see who was around. 
</P>
<P>
 The crowd included Michael Ovitz, Jon Peters, Mark Canton, Rob Reiner, Barbara 
Davis and daughter Nancy Davis, Laura Dern and Jeff Goldblum, Pia Zadora and, 
from UCLA, Dr. Dennis Slamon and Dr. Susan Love. 
</P>
</TEXT>
