<HEADLINE>
<P>
CONSUMER BRIEFS: SAFETY BOARD ANNOUNCES RECALLS OF TOYS, BOOKS, BIKES, CHAIRS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 With the holiday shopping season under way, the Consumer Product Safety 
Commission has announced massive recalls of a number of products, most of which 
have small parts that might cause a child to choke. The makers of all the 
products have agreed to go along with the recalls. Most of the products can be 
taken back to where they were purchased for full refunds. The items include: 
</P>
<P>
 * The children's book "Christmas in the Manger" by Nola Buck and Felicia Bond 
(HarperCollins Inc.). Forty-six thousand copies are being recalled because one 
page is decorated with plastic jewels that can peel off and are small enough to 
be swallowed by small children. 
</P>
<P>
 * About 2.5 million beanbag chairs made by Baseline Design Division of Crain 
Industries Inc. of Fort Smith, Ark., and sold nationwide by Kmart Corp., 
Wal-Mart Stores Inc. and other big retailers. Agency Chairman Ann Brown said a 
19-month-old Missouri boy died after he unzipped the bag and crawled inside, 
and one girl nearly suffocated after her brother zipped her inside a chair. The 
maker has offered to replace the chairs with new ones that don't have zippers, 
Brown said. Other beanbag-chair makers are being urged to stop using zippers. 
</P>
<P>
 * Hasbro Inc.'s Kid Dimension's Littlest Pet Shop Tea Sets. The small plastic 
animals on the teapot and sugar bowl can come off and become choking hazards. 
</P>
<P>
 * Imaginarium's $22.95 battery-operated "Fun Music Center," which has keys, 
drums, cymbals and two bells. It does not meet small-parts safety standards. 
</P>
<P>
 * A bicycles made by Specialized Bicycle Components Inc., Cannondale Corp. and 
the Fisher Bicycle Division of Trek Bicycle Corp. The agency said 186,700 are 
being recalled because their seat post bolts can break or crack, and another 
21,000 bikes made by Specialized, Answer Products Inc., Girvin Inc. and 
Marzocchi Suspension will be called in because of reports of front forks 
breaking. Riders can check with their bike shops to see if their models are on 
the recall list. 
</P>
</TEXT>
